{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17613877","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17613877"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:38:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:38:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16326"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9017"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114158"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9017"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96158"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7507"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21458"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114158"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe conjunctiva is a mucous membrane that covers parts of the eye and inner eyelids. It can be divided into distinct anatomical regions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following regions of the conjunctiva lines the inner surface of the eyelids and is divided into tarsal and orbital portions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bulbar conjunctiva","Fornical conjunctiva","Palpebral conjunctiva","Marginal conjunctiva","Caruncular conjunctiva"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epalpebral conjunctiva\u003C/strong\u003E lines the posterior surface of the eyelids and is divided into tarsal and orbital portions. The tarsal portion is firmly adherent to the tarsal plates, while the orbital portion is more loosely attached to the orbital septum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebulbar conjunctiva\u003C/strong\u003E covers the anterior portion of the eyeball up to the corneal limbus. The \u003Cstrong\u003Efornical conjunctiva\u003C/strong\u003E forms the loose fold that connects the bulbar and palpebral portions. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emarginal conjunctiva\u003C/strong\u003E is not a standard anatomical term for conjunctival regions. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaruncular conjunctiva\u003C/strong\u003E covers the caruncle, a small, pink nodule at the inner corner of the eye.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The palpebral conjunctiva lines the inner surface of the eyelids and is divided into tarsal and orbital portions.","The conjunctiva is a thin, transparent membrane that covers the anterior surface of the eye and inner surface of the eyelids."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Probst, L., \u0026 Tsai, J. (2024). Ophthalmology: Clinical and Surgical Principles. CRC Press","Salmon, J. F. (2024). Kanski\u0027s Clinical Ophthalmology E-Book: A Systematic Approach. Elsevier Health Sciences","Kels BD, Grzybowski A, Grant-Kels JM. Human ocular anatomy. Clin Dermatol. 2015 Mar-Apr;33(2):140-6. doi: 10.1016/j.clindermatol.2014.10.006. PMID: 25704934"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96158"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16326"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96158","links":{"self":"https://a